{"type":"message","id":"5ed11e0c","parentId":"b3c48d43","timestamp":"2026-05-13T09:46:36.468Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's only ONE openclaw gateway process running (pid 201984). That means all those sub-agents (tts, content, traffic, etc.) are NOT running as separate processes. They're just sessions within the gateway.\n\nSo the question \"why is the concurrency slow\" becomes clearer - there's only one gateway process handling everything, and it seems to be CPU-bound or event-loop bound.\n\nNow, the user is asking:\n1. My suggestion on the two options (sessions_send vs Feishu) + why is it suddenly slow\n2. About the enterprise Context Engine - what does it do, is it useful\n\nLet me address both clearly.\n\nFor the \"suddenly slow\" - looking at the logs again, the kiit session was already slow before I installed lossless-claw. The 585s long-running happened at 17:24, which is after I installed the plugin at ~17:20 but the issue pre-existed.\n \nThe real issue isn't lossless-claw itself - it's that the single gateway process is bottlenecked handling multiple concurrent sessions, and combined with MiniMax model latency, everything queues up and runs slowly. For the enterprise Context Engine, I installed lossless-claw as the context engine to replace the legacy one, and it should enable DAG-based summarization that preserves more context details during compaction so the model has better information to work with.\n\nThe key question is whether this actually improves response quality or if the latency is coming from something else entirely. Let me check the current session state to see what's happening.","thinkingSignature":"b611a9e14ace3f349b530c97680594a472450ed05b239462226e8fb02bee1e67"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0r4p5flml1wy_1","name":"session_status","arguments":{}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":359,"output":328,"cacheRead":66752,"cacheWrite